2) Configure wagmi + RainbowKit
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Below is an example using Next.js App Router. You’ll create a file in your project (e.g. wagmi/config.ts) that sets up the Wagmi client, RainbowKit, and your desired network.

wagmi/config.ts:

import { createConfig, configureChains } from 'wagmi';
import { mainnet, goerli, hardhat } from 'wagmi/chains';
import { publicProvider } from 'wagmi/providers/public';
import { getDefaultWallets } from '@rainbow-me/rainbowkit';

export const { chains, publicClient } = configureChains(
  // For local dev, replace goerli/mainnet with hardhat or your testnet chain
  [hardhat],
  [publicProvider()]
);

const { connectors } = getDefaultWallets({
  appName: 'PokemonDefi App',
  chains
});

export const wagmiConfig = createConfig({
  autoConnect: true,
  connectors,
  publicClient
});

Then in app/layout.tsx (or a custom provider component), you can wrap your app with RainbowKit and Wagmi:

layout.tsx (or a dedicated providers.tsx):

'use client';

import './globals.css';
import { Inter } from 'next/font/google';
import { RainbowKitProvider } from '@rainbow-me/rainbowkit';
import { WagmiConfig } from 'wagmi';
import '@rainbow-me/rainbowkit/styles.css';
import { wagmiConfig, chains } from '../wagmi/config';

const inter = Inter({ subsets: ['latin'] });

export default function RootLayout({
  children,
}: {
  children: React.ReactNode
}) {
  return (
    <html lang="en">
      <body className={inter.className}>
        <WagmiConfig config={wagmiConfig}>
          <RainbowKitProvider chains={chains}>
            {children}
          </RainbowKitProvider>
        </WagmiConfig>
      </body>
    </html>
  );
}

Now your entire Next.js app has wallet connectivity with wagmi, RainbowKit, and the local Hardhat chain (or any testnet you choose).

